Habitat varied... Lake: Open water unless otherwise stated. 45-50F, partly cloudy, windy. The viewing area at the City of Henderson''s Wastewater Treatment Facility encompasses over 200 acres of ponds, lagoons and basins. The checklist compiled by the Red Rock Audubon Society has 188 birds on it.----This was the Red Cliffs Audubon (St. George) March field trip to Las Vegas and the City of Henderson''s Bird Viewing Preserve. In total we saw 52 species, 45 of those was at the preserve. The rest were at the Ethel M Chocolates manufacturing facility, where there is a rather extensive cactus garden. ----Observers: Myself and Charlie Sheard.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS31351102	2018-08-04 08:58:16	5587	species	American Avocet	Recurvirostra americana			36				United States	US	Nevada	US-NV	Clark	US-NV-003		33			Henderson Bird Viewing Preserve	L209342	H	36.0749791	-115.0021416	2006-04-14	10:00:00	obsr91229	S2289923	Incidental	P20	EBIRD	180	2.092		2	1		0	1	0		A somewhat overcast day, with a few raindrops.  While we arrived late, the cloud cover had kept the temperature down.  Still, we missed many things we might have seen because of the lateness of the day.  The Purple Martins were the highlight - two females and a male - because of their unexpectedness.  We left a full report with the staff.  The Common Moorhens were everywhere - including some babies.  The number surprised us too, but if anything it is an underestimate.  Same with the abundance of Eared Grebes.  The takover of Pond 9 by the Great-tailed Grackles makes this number (54) a likely underestimate.  Absence of all diurnal birds of prey odd; saddened by lack of rails or bitterns.  All-in-all a splendid morning, despite the timing and weather.

Habitat varied... Lake: Open water unless otherwise stated. 80F, clear, high clouds by end of visit with light breeze. The viewing area at the City of Henderson''s Wastewater Treatment Facility encompasses over 200 acres of ponds, lagoons and basins. The checklist compiled by the Red Rock Audubon Society has 250 birds on it.----This was the Red Cliffs Audubon (St. George) April field trip to Las Vegas and the City of Henderson''s Bird Viewing Preserve. In total we saw 35 species, 32 of those was at the preserve. The rest were on the road down from St. George along I-15.----Observers: Myself, Carl Berger, Marilyn Davis, Denise Blynn three others.

This birding was for the Nevada Breeding Bird Atlas work conducted by Marshall Iliff and Brian Sullivan. We worked a different atlas block from the morning, this one at a ranch a few miles west of town. We asked permission to walk around and then split up and did separate wide loops. Marshall headed north and east and then walked the sagebrush margins to the west before looping back. Brian stayed closer to the ranchyard. Brian identified an Upland Sandpiper at the time, largely by call, but missed the vocal Long-billed Curlews and was unfamiliar with their call. I am not sure of Brian''s current opinion on Upland Sandpiper, but it would have represented a 3rd state record. We looked for his sandpiper for a while that afternoon and again the next morning to no avail. Start time, duration, and mileage are estimates.

Various habitats - see listings. 59-68F, partly cloudy with high thin clouds thickening as the day progressed only to move on by midafternoon, leaving a clear sunny sky, with a south breeze/wind. A nice day for birding.----This is the November field trip for Red Cliffs Audubon out of St. George. Our focus was the refuge in central Nevada on Hwy 93. The lower lake and Maynard lake are dry. But Upper Lake and North Marsh are significant bodies of water. While birding focused on the refuge, birding was done at several locations prior to reaching Pahranagat.----Observers: Myself, Charlie Sheard, Kevin Wheeler and 8 others.	Lake: Mudflats.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS56298787	2017-04-18 17:05:33	5587	species	American Avocet	Recurvirostra americana			5				United States	US	Nevada	US-NV	Nye	US-NV-023	US-NV_977	33	USFWS_350		Ash Meadows NWR HQ	L388900	H	36.4204294	-116.3299853	1965-04-14	06:15:00	obsr56422	S4058241	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	405	4.023	4.0469	2	1		0	1	0		Potash Springs, Longstreet Springs, Frog Springs and Rodgers Springs. Habitat varies, see bird notes. 55F, warm, sunny. This is a Desert Ecology Class, Chico State College. We are in the northern end of Ash Meadows in western Nevada. It is a hot, arid land with steep rising mountains which almost totally lack any type of vegetation. Potash Springs, one mile north of Longstreet Springs was where we camped. The springs are an oasis in the desert. Vegetation is very sparse and located primarily around these springs. Plants are Tamarisk, willow, cottonwood,  and some sedges. Away from water the basic shrubs are Mesquite. Some succulents and Creosote present. Buildings at the various sights were built around 1860. Potash Springs is approx. 4 miles west of SR29 and about 10 miles south of Lathrop Wells, NV. Frog Springs and Rodger Springs are located inbetween Potash and Longstreet Springs.----Observers: Myself and Dr. Dempsey----Footnote: 8PM, Lou Davis and I went north 19 miles to some sand dunes. Only insect present were 3 beetles, some grubs and 5 Dune Crickets. These crickets never before found this far north. All beetles proceeding up dunes, none down. When sand was pushed down, beetles always remained on top or ahead of moving sand. 10PM	Potash Springs. Lake: Mudflats.

Emphasize particularly the marks used to identify the bird, but include a complete description of the bird.  Include size, overall shape, plumage and color pattern; details on shape or size of bill, wings, and tail.  Describe what you are actually observing in the field.----A duck, virtually identical in size and structure to nearby American Wigeons.  Pale gray flanks and on back fading to slightly brownish on wing tips.  Pale pinkish/rose-colored on breast.  White on abdomen and a band above the base of the tail.  The tail was black.  The head and neck were bright maroon-rufous with a buffy-white disk on the forehead.  The bird had white horizontal bars along the flanks about 1/3 of the way down the body.  ----Describe the bird's overall behavior:--The bird was closely associating with a flock of American Wigeons.  Foraging actively in sahllow water and at times resting on a mud flat.  A few times I noted aggressive encounters with other male wigeons. ----Describe the habitat in which you observed the bird:--Medium sized man-made reservoir.  The flock was sticking close to the edge of the reservoir lined partially with cattail marsh and partially with an alkaline mud flat.  Surrounding matrix of of saltbush desert scrub, sedge meadows, and young ash groves.----Describe the bird's calls or sounds, if heard, including method of delivery, i.e., from perch, in flight, etc.:  Did not vocalize during any of my observations.----List similar species and how you eliminated them:  Easily separated from American Wigeon by rufous head and neck, buffy-white forehead disk, uniform gray flanks, lack of green on head.  The bird was closely examined for features consistent with American Wigeon and none were detected, eliminating the possibility of a hybrid.--Prior experience with this and similar species:  I have seen this species in several consecutive winters in Albuquerque NM, often at close range, once in Scottsdale AZ, and once at Bolinas Lagoon in northern California.----Optical equipment:--Viewed through Nikon Prostaff 20-60X82 Spotting Scope.----If photographed, please enclose a copy or attach digital copy to email.  --Photo equipment used:  Digiscoped using above mentioned spotting scope and a rather cheap Olympus digital camera.----Other observers who independently identified the bird (please list name and address if known):--None----Additional discussion:----References consulted:--None needed.----This report was written from notes made during _X_ after ___ observation (from memory).--If "after, from memory", approximately how long after the observation were notes first written:------Name: Carl G. The train had t stop briefly several times (why, I don't for sure). We were in the observation car when we saw these birds as we crossed northern Nevada. Based on the time that the train was scheduled to arrive in Reno (mid morning) I figured that we were in Pershing County. And Rye Patch Reservoir is the only place that I can find on the map that makes sense for our location, based on the size of the body of water we were passing slowly by, and species that my wife and I saw.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS32283139	2018-08-04 08:57:26	5587	species	American Avocet	Recurvirostra americana			80				United States	US	Nevada	US-NV	Washoe	US-NV-031	US-NV_1107	9			Swan Lake Nature Study Area (IBA)	L124349	H	39.6574142	-119.8457766	2000-07-30		obsr16674	S2348628	Incidental	P20	EBIRD				3	1		0	1	0		Hello, everybody.  Tim Lenz, John Anderson, and I visited --&gt; Lemmon Valley Marsh on a hot Sunday afternoon (30 July --&gt; 2000).  Lemmon Valley Marsh is just north of Reno, in --&gt; Washoe County.  Our quest was shorebirds, of which we --&gt; found a few, as follows: --&gt; --&gt; 1. Killdeer               200 --&gt; 2. American Avocet         80 --&gt; 3. Black-necked Stilt     390 --&gt; 4. Willet                   1 --&gt; 5. Marbled Godwit           1 --&gt; 6. Long-billed Dowitcher    6 --&gt; 7. Wilson's Phalarope      10 --&gt; 8. Red-necked Phalarope    20 --&gt;    phalarope, sp.          40 --&gt; --&gt; Other birds observed included: large numbers of White-faced --&gt; Ibises; good numbers and variety of dabbling ducks (including --&gt; a Ruddy Duck who looked like he had just dipped his bill in --&gt; a bucket of blue paint); a calling Sora; lots of California --&gt; Gulls and a few Ring-billed Gulls; a truly bedraggled-looking --&gt; largish gull that we couldn't identify, but which looked --&gt; interesting; and a few Bank Swallows (yesterday Tim saw about --&gt; 20 at this site). --&gt; --&gt; Large numbers of birds are using Lemmon Valley Marsh now, --&gt; and seekers of rarities should definitely be checking those --&gt; ibis, duck, and gull flocks for rarities wandering northward --&gt; from their breeding grounds!	Lemmon Valley Marsh, w Tim Lenz, Ted Floyd
